facts.value: His early life was passed on the farm and in a manner common with pioneer boys; school advantages were poor, and he only received such education as could be gotten in the subscription school. He remained at home with his parents till his marriage. After that he continued on the old home farm as before. His entire life's work  was on the land that his father and grandfather before him. H owned 160 acres. He was a modest and unassuming gentleman with no desire  whatever for notoriety, and has never been an aspirant for the empty bauble of local office. To the Mason Horse Ranges he has belonged since the organization of the society, and is a republican in politics.
